{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T13:54:14.429706+00:00", "modified": "2025-10-06T19:14:29.623719+00:00", "id": 13488547, "conceptrecid": "13488546", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13488547", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13488546", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13488547", "metadata": {"title": "Re-examining extreme sleep duration in bats: implications for sleep phylogeny, ecology, and function", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13488547", "publication_date": "2022", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Bats, quoted as sleeping for up to 20 h a day, are an often used example of extreme sleep duration amongst mammals. Given that duration has historically been one of the primary metrics featured in comparative studies of sleep, it is important that species specific sleep durations are well founded. Here, we re-examined the evidence for the characterization of bats as extreme sleepers and discuss whether it provides a useful representation of the sleep behavior of Chiroptera. Although there are a wealth of activity data to suggest that the diurnal cycle of bats is dominated by rest, estimates of sleep time generated from electrophysiological analyses suggest considerable interspecific variation, ranging from 83% to a more moderate 61% of the 24 h day spent asleep. Temperature-dependent changes in the duration and electroencephalographic profile of sleep suggest that bats represent a unique model for investigating the relationship between sleep and torpor. Further sources of intra-specific variation in sleep duration, including the impact of artificial laboratory environments and sleep intensity, remain unexplored. Future studies conducted in naturalistic environments, using larger sample sizes and relying on a predetermined set of defining criteria will undoubtedly provide novel insights into sleep in bats and other species.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Harding, Christian D", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Yovel, Yossi", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Peirson, Stuart N", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Hackett, Talya D", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Vyazovskiy, Vladyslav V", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/97a5d227f4dac91c72b31adc3e2c1887", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/b594e0772152946ebac13b7e05024e93a14d7c4f7a484d569d54f1930a4f71aa", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/VNP87S42", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/VNP87S42", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/f60b4f57b979063fa7c5cc3fc3201bc1!/b231813-234371", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/330417efcaa2560c9b8ebcd6fae17ce0", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "publication", "subtype": "article"}, "journal": {"issue": "8", "pages": "zsac064", "title": "Sleep", "volume": "45"}, "alternate_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/97a5d227f4dac91c72b31adc3e2c1887"}, {"identifier": "urn:lsid:zotero.org:groups:5435545:items:VNP87S42"}, {"identifier": "10.1093/sleep/zsac064"}], "communities": [{"id": "biosyslit"}, {"id": "batlit"}], "relations": {"version": [{"index": 0, "is_last": true, "parent": {"pid_type": "recid", "pid_value": "13488546"}}]}}, "title": "Re-examining extreme sleep duration in bats: implications for sleep phylogeny, ecology, and function", "links": {"self": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/13488547